{
  "id": "jsonbored_metagraphed_1379",
  "repo_name": "jsonbored/metagraphed",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/jsonbored/metagraphed",
  "base_commit": "917c79a486324e8331c21e868c0ef003d06d53cc",
  "pr_number": 1379,
  "issue_number": 1377,
  "issue_title": "fix(mcp): find_subnet_for_task drops callable subnets \u2014 filters callability after truncating the rank pool",
  "issue_body": "## Summary\n\nThe MCP tool `find_subnet_for_task` ([`src/mcp-server.mjs`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L1146)) ranks the **entire** subnet index, truncates to a fixed pool of 50, and **only then** filters down to subnets that actually expose callable services. When 50+ non-callable subnets out-rank a callable one for the task term, the callable subnet is silently cut from the pool \u2014 so the tool returns **fewer than `limit` results, or zero**, and emits the misleading note *\"No callable subnet matched this task.\"* even though a callable subnet genuinely matches.\n\nThis is the inverse of the order used by the sibling tool `find_subnets_by_capability` ([`src/mcp-server.mjs`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L629-L654)), which filters `callable_count > 0` **before** `.slice(0, limit)`. The asymmetry is the bug: a goal-shaped tool whose entire contract is *\"return subnets that can do this task\"* must apply the callability filter before the pool is cut, not after.\n\n## Where\n\n`rankSubnetsForTask` (keyword branch) \u2014 [`src/mcp-server.mjs:281-290`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L281-L290):\n\n```js\nconst ranked = docs\n  .filter((doc) => doc.type === \"subnet\")\n  .map((doc) => ({\n    netuid: doc.netuid,\n    relevance: scoreDocument(doc, terms),\n  }))\n  .filter((entry) => entry.relevance > 0)\n  .sort((a, b) => b.relevance - a.relevance || a.netuid - b.netuid)\n  .slice(0, poolSize);          // <-- truncates to 50 BEFORE callability is known\nreturn { mode: \"keyword\", ranked };\n```\n\nThe handler then joins this already-truncated pool against the callable catalog \u2014 [`src/mcp-server.mjs:1149-1175`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L1149-L1175):\n\n```js\nconst { mode, ranked } = await rankSubnetsForTask(ctx, task, 50);\nconst catalog = await loadArtifactData(ctx, \"/metagraph/agent-catalog.json\");\nconst byNetuid = new Map((catalog.subnets || []).map((entry) => [entry.netuid, entry]));\nconst results = [];\nfor (const { netuid, relevance } of ranked) {\n  const entry = byNetuid.get(netuid);\n  if (!entry) continue;          // <-- callability filter, AFTER the slice(0, 50)\n  results.push({ /* ... */ });\n  if (results.length >= limit) break;\n}\n```\n\n`search.json` (the rank source) contains **all** enriched subnets; `agent-catalog.json` (the join target) contains **only** subnets exposing callable services. So the callability constraint is applied a full step too late \u2014 after the top-50 cut has already discarded callable candidates.\n\n## Why it's wrong\n\n`find_subnets_by_capability` demonstrates the correct order \u2014 it ranks over the catalog and filters callability **before** truncating ([`src/mcp-server.mjs:646-654`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L646-L654)):\n\n```js\n.filter((entry) => entry.score > 0 && entry.subnet.callable_count > 0)   // filter first\n.sort(/* ... */)\n.slice(0, limit);                                                         // then truncate\n```\n\n`find_subnet_for_task` does the opposite. Because the truncation (`poolSize = 50`) happens before callability is consulted, any callable subnet whose relevance ranks it at position 51+ \u2014 behind 50 non-callable matches \u2014 is dropped before the handler ever sees it.\n\n## Concrete trigger\n\nA common, generic task term (e.g. `\"data\"`, `\"image\"`, `\"inference\"`, `\"api\"`) that matches many subnets via the enriched `categories` / `service_kinds` index. If 50+ subnets **without** callable services score at least as high as the callable ones, the callable subnets fall outside the top-50 pool.\n\nMinimal reproduction (keyword path, AI disabled): a `search.json` containing 55 non-callable subnets whose enrichment strongly matches the term, plus one callable subnet (in `agent-catalog.json`) that matches the same term more weakly. `find_subnet_for_task({ task: \"<term>\", limit: 5 })` returns:\n\n```\ndiscovery: keyword\ncount: 0\nresults: []\nnote: \"No callable subnet matched this task. Try rephrasing, or use find_subnets_by_capability...\"\n```\n\nThe callable subnet exists and matches, but ranked at pool position 56 (> 50) it is truncated away. The semantic branch ([`src/mcp-server.mjs:266-273`](src/mcp-server.mjs#L266-L273)) has the same filter-after-pool shape with an even smaller effective pool (`SEMANTIC_MAX_LIMIT = 20`), so it under-returns even more readily, and it commits to `mode: \"semantic\"` (returning empty) instead of falling back to keyword discovery.\n\n## User-visible impact\n\n`find_subnet_for_task` is a primary agent-facing discovery tool \u2014 its whole purpose is to answer *\"which subnet can do X.\"* The bug makes it return an empty result set with a definitive *\"No callable subnet matched this task\"* for exactly the broad, popular task terms it most needs to serve. AI agents calling the public MCP endpoint get a false dead-end and stop, hiding subnets that genuinely expose the requested capability. The failure is silent (a normal 200 with `count: 0`), so it looks like a correct \"nothing matches\" answer rather than a truncation artifact.\n\n## Proposed fix\n\nApply the callability filter **before** the pool is truncated, mirroring `find_subnets_by_capability`. Load the callable catalog first and pass it into `rankSubnetsForTask` so both the keyword and semantic branches rank only over callable subnets:\n\n- Handler: load `agent-catalog.json` and build the `byNetuid` map first, then call `rankSubnetsForTask(ctx, task, 50, byNetuid)`.\n- Keyword branch: add `&& byNetuid.has(entry.netuid)` to the `.filter(...)` that precedes `.slice(0, poolSize)`.\n- Semantic branch: filter the mapped results to `byNetuid.has(r.netuid)` before the `ranked.length > 0` check, so a pool of only non-callable hits falls through to keyword discovery instead of committing to `mode: \"semantic\"` with an empty result.\n\nThe handler's existing `if (!entry) continue` stays as a harmless safety net. Net effect: the top-`limit` *callable* matches always surface, and the tool only reports \"no callable subnet\" when there truly is none.\n\nAdd a regression test (keyword path, AI disabled) with 50+ non-callable subnets out-ranking one callable subnet, asserting the callable subnet is returned (`count === 1`) rather than `0`.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `src/mcp-server.mjs` \u2014 `rankSubnetsForTask` + the `find_subnet_for_task` handler. No new dependencies.\n- No schema, OpenAPI, or generated-artifact changes \u2014 the tool's output shape is unchanged; only which subnets it surfaces becomes correct.\n- Add/adjust a test under `tests/mcp-server.test.mjs`.",
  "merged_at": "2026-06-22T07:32:29.000Z",
